they grapple with complex issues of identity and societal belonging in the ethnic homeland. This book demonstrates how these professional migrants maneuver between countries and cultures to further their careers and maximize opportunities in the rapidly changing global economy. When used strategically, the versatile nature of their ethnic identities positions them as indispensable bridges between the global superpowers of China and the United States in their competition for global dominance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican Dream. 0aAmericanszChinaxSocial conditions. 0aChinese AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aChinese AmericanszChina. 0aImmigrantszChinaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aChina, middle-class children of immigrants, middle-class children, American-born Chinese, American-born Chinese professionals, People’s Republic of China, global dominance, professional migrants, second-generation, ethnic homeland, highly educated, transnationalism, United States, Ancestral Homeland, belonging, American Dream, american, chinese, gendered experiences, american identity, identity, Chinese American, citizen, citizenship, race, ethnicity, racial identity, minority.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081359940340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813599403423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813599403/original  a978-3-11-073913-8  Rutgers U